data.chText: 身份（或地位）相同的人；同龄人；同辈
data.enText: a person who is the same age or who has the same social status as you
She enjoys the respect of her peers.

data.chText: 儿童都怕在同伴面前失败。
data.enText: Children are worried about failing in front of their peers.

data.chText: 年轻人受到强大的同辈压力。
data.enText: Peer pressure is strong among young people (= they want to be like other people of the same age) .
(in Britain) a member of the nobility
to look closely or carefully at sth, especially when you cannot see it clearly
We peered into the shadows.

data.chText: 他走到窗前仔细往外瞧。
data.enText: He went to the window and peered out.
She kept peering over her shoulder.

data.chText: 他聚精会神地端详着相片。
data.enText: He peered closely at the photograph.

data.chText: 以上各词均含盯着看、凝视、注视之义。
data.enText: These words all mean to look at sb/sth for a long time.
stare

data.chText: 尤指吃惊、害怕或深思地盯着看、凝视、注视：
data.enText: to look at sb/sth for a long time, especially with surprise or fear, or because you are thinking

data.chText: 我尖叫一声，众人都盯着我看。
data.enText: I screamed and everyone stared.
gaze

data.chText: 尤指吃惊、爱恋或深思地凝视、注视、盯着：
data.enText: ( rather formal ) to look steadily at sb/sth for a long time, especially with surprise or love, or because you are thinking

data.chText: 我们都惊异地注视着马可。
data.enText: We all gazed at Marco in amazement.
peer

data.chText: 尤指看不清楚时仔细看、端详
data.enText: to look closely or carefully at sth, especially when you cannot see it clearly
glare
to look angrily at sb/sth for a long time

data.chText: 我看了她一眼，她便冷冷地回瞪着我。
data.enText: I looked at her and she glared stonily back.
to stare/gaze/peer/glare at sb/sth
to stare/gaze/peer/glare hard/intently/suspiciously
to stare/gaze/peer anxiously/nervously
to stare/gaze/glare fiercely/stonily
to stare/gaze wide-eyed/open-mouthed
to stare/gaze into space

tr: a person who is of equal standing with another in a group
a nobleman (duke or marquis or earl or viscount or baron) who is a member of the British peerage

example: We peered into the back of the shop to see whether a salesman was around

value.def: If you peer at something, you look at it very hard, usually because it is difficult to see clearly.

example.ex: I had been peering at a computer print-out that made no sense at all...
example.tran: 我一直盯着看一张毫无意义的计算机打印稿。

example.ex: He watched the Customs official peer into the driver's window.
example.tran: 他看见海关官员透过驾驶座车窗仔细地往里看。

value.tran: （通常因难以看清而）盯着看，凝视，端详

value.def: In Britain, a peer is a member of the nobility who has or had the right to vote in the House of Lords.

example.ex: Lord Swan was made a life peer in 1981.
example.tran: 斯旺勋爵于1981年受封终身贵族。

value.tran: （英国有权或曾经有权在上议院投票的）贵族

value.def: Your peers are the people who are the same age as you or who have the same status as you.

example.ex: ...children who are much cleverer than their peers...
example.tran: 比同龄人聪明许多的孩子

example.ex: His engaging personality made him popular with his peers.
example.tran: 他迷人的个性使他深受同龄人的喜爱。

value.tran: 同龄人；同辈；身份（或地位）相同的人

trans: 同行评审；同行审阅；同侪互评；同行审查；同行评估；同行评价
来自同伴的压力；同侪压力；同辈压力
同龄群体；社会地位相同的群体
